snippet.textDisplay:
It will all depend how much energy is left in the tank for Federer. In his last three encounters at AO 2020, he is been out on court playing 2 five sets and 1 four set matches. Considering his age, agility and stamina...I don't know how much he has left to tackle an opponent who is playing possibly his best tennis, booming with confidence and both mentally and physically stronger but then again what is on paper doesn't always transcends. Let's hope Federer gets some rest and we get to watch the best of the bests in action. In my opinion apart from the 2019 Wimbledon Championships Final, I think the best match between Djokovic and Federer was 2011 Roland Garros Semi-Final. One of the best matches Federer ever played. Djokovic was in a dangerous form and on a 42 match winning streak. Rafa would have lost in 2011 Roland Garros Final if Federer didn't stop Djokovic.


Having said that, well played Sandgren even though you lost you are champ (injuries always suck) and Congrats Roger!!

snippet.textDisplay: A reminder that luck is a factor. You’ll hear many times, especially from the Big Three, that’s luck was a factor is some of their important matches. snippet.textDisplay: Federer is very good tennis player.  However in my analysis,  he did not really got injured during the match.  The way he played and moved in the fourth and final set does't look that he has a serious injury.  He misses a lot because of the strong serve and return of Sandgren,  it gives a lot pressures to him  as a result it loses his timing.    I guess, but not really sure ... Fed uses the medical time-out to break the rhythm and pressure from his opponent.   It was too long actually,  it should be 3 minutes only but the medical time-out lasted for 8 minutes.    But nevertheless Fed is still a great tennis player.  If he's really injured,  he will full-out during the match with Djokovic.  Because Injured muscle is really difficult to recover in one day.  Worst it will start to cause pain.  If ... that injury is really true ... because he was away from the court for 8 minutes.

snippet.textDisplay: 2 miraculous escapes in this tournament. Absolutely phenomenal. The legend has nothing to prove to anyone anymore but continues playing for his love of the sport and continues to amaze us. Im so so happy hes reached the semis at his age. Its already a great achievement considering the positions he was in against Millman and Sandgren who both played superb matches, but Federer showed Nadal like fighting spirit and refused to be beaten. Not sure how much he will have left in the tank against Novak, but i dont expect anything more tbh, hes given us so much to cheer about. Lets just hope he plays with nothing to lose and freely with no pressure.
